nical outflow with velocities up to ~200\nkm/s. H{\\alpha} emission traces instead star formation in a circumnuclear ring\nand along the bar, where we detect non-circular motions. Soft X-rays are mostly\ndue to thermal emission from the star-forming regions, but we could isolate the\nAGN photoionized component which matches the [OIII] emission. The mass outflow\nrate of the extended ionized outflow matches that of the nuclear X-ray wind and\nthen decreases with radius. However, the hard X-ray emission from the\ncircumnuclear ring suggests that star formation might contribute to the\noutflow. The integrated mass outflow rate, kinetic energy rate, and outflow\nvelocity are broadly consistent with the typical relations observed in more\nluminous AGN.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Tue, 4 Sep 2018 19:09:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2018-11-14"}
